1
00:00:00,789 --> 00:00:05,770
Most of the information you can find online
is usually all about retail trading.

2
00:00:05,770 --> 00:00:09,660
If you look for institutional trading, you
can’t find much about it.

3
00:00:09,660 --> 00:00:15,230
Smart Money trading is perhaps one of the
best kept secrets in the world of trading.

4
00:00:15,230 --> 00:00:20,480
Once you discover institutional trading and
learn how Smart Money place their orders,

5
00:00:20,480 --> 00:00:26,230
you can implement these concepts to your own
style of trading and see much better results.

6
00:00:26,230 --> 00:00:31,160
So let me show you several smart money concepts
you must follow, in order to finally become

7
00:00:31,160 --> 00:00:33,380
a profitable trader.

8
00:00:33,380 --> 00:00:39,160
Indicators Lag, Price Action Leads

9
00:00:39,160 --> 00:00:44,690
There is no indicator, Forex robot, or mechanical
trading system that will make you money if

10
00:00:44,690 --> 00:00:48,230
you don’t understand how and why price moves.

11
00:00:48,230 --> 00:00:52,989
In reality, if you rely your decisions on
indicators, you’re not really trading the

12
00:00:52,989 --> 00:00:58,400
market, you’re really just plugging numbers
into a few mathematical formulas.

13
00:00:58,400 --> 00:01:00,780
Indicators have absolutely no flexibility.

14
00:01:00,780 --> 00:01:06,670
They are just an equation that is used over
and over again, regardless of market conditions.

15
00:01:06,670 --> 00:01:13,390
Stochastics, MACD and a load of other indicators
are presenting you with lagging information.

16
00:01:13,390 --> 00:01:18,390
They may look pretty on your chart, and can
help you to some degree to view a market,

17
00:01:18,390 --> 00:01:23,270
but they don’t really help you predict where
the price is going in the future.

18
00:01:23,270 --> 00:01:27,409
Indicators show you what has happened in the
past, but they won’t tell you what price

19
00:01:27,409 --> 00:01:30,940
is going to do in the future.

20
00:01:30,940 --> 00:01:34,700
Indicators used to be a powerful tool, but
those days have passed.

21
00:01:34,700 --> 00:01:41,200
Stochastic was created in 1950′s, MACD in
1960′s and RSI 1970′s.

22
00:01:41,200 --> 00:01:42,770
Do you see the connection?

23
00:01:42,770 --> 00:01:48,840
These lagging indicators were in use before
modern computer systems took over the trading

24
00:01:48,840 --> 00:01:49,840
world!

25
00:01:49,840 --> 00:01:55,310
The problem is that even though computers
were invented, and people got access to technology,

26
00:01:55,310 --> 00:01:59,530
they never moved away from the old way of
viewing the market.

27
00:01:59,530 --> 00:02:03,170
Trading without indicators is just like eliminating
the middle man.

28
00:02:03,170 --> 00:02:08,039
Instead of letting indicators to tell you
what the market is doing, you can see it for

29
00:02:08,039 --> 00:02:09,039
yourself.

30
00:02:09,039 --> 00:02:13,310
So, the first step, try trading for a few
weeks without indicators.

31
00:02:13,310 --> 00:02:20,430
Support and resistance levels are good, but
supply and demand areas are better

32
00:02:20,430 --> 00:02:25,640
Any chart is a sequence of zones where there
is supply and demand equilibrium, with supply

33
00:02:25,640 --> 00:02:28,120
and demand imbalances in between.

34
00:02:28,120 --> 00:02:32,469
If you are re used to trade classic support
and resistance level, I advise you to forget

35
00:02:32,469 --> 00:02:36,530
about them for a second, and focus on supply
and demand zones.

36
00:02:36,530 --> 00:02:41,809
Especially, the zones where the price is moving
away from with a lot of momentum.

37
00:02:41,809 --> 00:02:46,510
Whenever that happens, it’s a sign that
the balance of supply and demand has shifted

38
00:02:46,510 --> 00:02:48,420
in a very substantial way.

39
00:02:48,420 --> 00:02:52,709
Supply and demand zones are the origins of
these price moves.

40
00:02:52,709 --> 00:02:58,029
A supply zone is an area at which a lot of
sudden selling has occurred.

41
00:02:58,029 --> 00:03:02,949
This resulted in an imbalance between supply
and demand, where supply greatly exceeded

42
00:03:02,949 --> 00:03:05,719
demand, pushing the price down.

43
00:03:05,719 --> 00:03:10,329
A demand zone is an area at which a lot of
sudden buying has occurred.

44
00:03:10,329 --> 00:03:15,439
This resulted in an imbalance between supply
and demand, where demand greatly exceeded

45
00:03:15,439 --> 00:03:17,390
supply, pushing the price up.

46
00:03:17,390 --> 00:03:21,209
I consider supply and demand as a leading
indicator.

47
00:03:21,209 --> 00:03:26,370
While traditionally, support and resistance
levels are only called as such after at least

48
00:03:26,370 --> 00:03:29,950
two tests, this is not the case with supply
and demand.

49
00:03:29,950 --> 00:03:36,829
You only need a supply or demand zone to be
created in order to plan a potential trade.

50
00:03:36,829 --> 00:03:40,400
So use the following steps to identify supply
and demand:

51
00:03:40,400 --> 00:03:41,400
1.

52
00:03:41,400 --> 00:03:45,879
Find the Momentum Drive
Here you’re looking for a large price move.

53
00:03:45,879 --> 00:03:49,949
Long, successive candles in one direction
work the best.

54
00:03:49,949 --> 00:03:54,090
Just open any chart and it shouldn’t be
too difficult to find those.

55
00:03:54,090 --> 00:04:00,530
Both the momentum (how fast is the price moving)
and the absolute distance (for far did the

56
00:04:00,530 --> 00:04:05,409
price move before it stopped going in that
direction) are relevant here.

57
00:04:05,409 --> 00:04:10,089
Of course, the best price moves show both
momentum and a large absolute distance.

58
00:04:10,089 --> 00:04:11,089
2.

59
00:04:11,089 --> 00:04:13,880
Find the Base of the Momentum Drive
After you have found the momentum drive, you

60
00:04:13,880 --> 00:04:16,040
should define your base.

61
00:04:16,040 --> 00:04:21,480
With the base, I mean the price area just
before the price exploded in one direction.

62
00:04:21,480 --> 00:04:27,090
Often, you will see a small consolidation
before this happens and that’s the consolidation

63
00:04:27,090 --> 00:04:28,660
that you’re looking for.

64
00:04:28,660 --> 00:04:32,770
Especially, try to find:
• the last bearish price action before a

65
00:04:32,770 --> 00:04:37,090
bullish price move
• the last bullish price action before a

66
00:04:37,090 --> 00:04:42,130
bearish price move
This is the area that is responsible for the

67
00:04:42,130 --> 00:04:47,150
resulting move: The base of a supply or demand
zone is where the orders were placed that

68
00:04:47,150 --> 00:04:51,440
were responsible for moving the market in
such a strong way.

69
00:04:51,440 --> 00:04:58,250
VSA will make the difference between a losing
and a winner trade

70
00:04:58,250 --> 00:05:02,900
Volume is not difficult to understand once
the basic principles of supply and demand

71
00:05:02,900 --> 00:05:04,450
are understood.

72
00:05:04,450 --> 00:05:08,180
This requires you to relate the volume with
price action.

73
00:05:08,180 --> 00:05:13,060
To say that the market will go up when there
is more buying (demand) than selling – and

74
00:05:13,060 --> 00:05:18,950
go down when there is more selling (supply)
than buying may seem like an obvious statement.

75
00:05:18,950 --> 00:05:23,400
To understand what the volume is saying to
you, you have to ask yourself “What has

76
00:05:23,400 --> 00:05:26,590
the price done on a particular volume”?

77
00:05:26,590 --> 00:05:31,490
Think about it, if you compare today's volume
with volume during the previous thirty bars,

78
00:05:31,490 --> 00:05:35,170
it is easy to see if today's volume is higher
or lower.

79
00:05:35,170 --> 00:05:39,840
But you took volume in isolation, and that’s
means very little.

80
00:05:39,840 --> 00:05:44,460
Compare this volume information with the price
spread and you will then know how bullish

81
00:05:44,460 --> 00:05:48,190
or bearish the market really is.

82
00:05:48,190 --> 00:05:54,790
Volume spread analysis is the type of analysis
based on volumes and the spread of the candlestick.

83
00:05:54,790 --> 00:05:58,820
It tries to find out the differences between
supply and demand.

84
00:05:58,820 --> 00:06:03,990
The price spread is the difference between
the highest and lowest trading points reached

85
00:06:03,990 --> 00:06:09,070
during the timeframe you are looking at, which
may be weekly, daily, hourly, or whatever

86
00:06:09,070 --> 00:06:11,340
other timeframe you choose.

87
00:06:11,340 --> 00:06:15,570
Some traders consider the actual body of the
candle, as the spread.

88
00:06:15,570 --> 00:06:18,060
You decide which method you want to apply.

89
00:06:18,060 --> 00:06:23,490
There are a lot of different interpretations
of the VSA, which makes it difficult to understand

90
00:06:23,490 --> 00:06:25,780
it for a beginner trader.

91
00:06:25,780 --> 00:06:31,440
At first, you need to get familiarized with
the most commonly used models of the VSA,

92
00:06:31,440 --> 00:06:36,140
so make sure you watch this video about volume
spread analysis after you finish this one.

93
00:06:36,140 --> 00:06:38,690
Smart money relies on retail traders to provide
liquidity.

94
00:06:38,690 --> 00:06:42,960
Smart money will push price to an area where
retail traders place their stop loss.

95
00:06:42,960 --> 00:06:49,120
In order to understand why supply and demand
zones can work as the basis of a trading strategy,

96
00:06:49,120 --> 00:06:54,000
you need to understand how buyers and sellers
behave around these zones.

97
00:06:54,000 --> 00:06:57,270
A lot of this comes down to finding liquidity.

98
00:06:57,270 --> 00:07:01,450
Liquidity describes how easily an asset can
be bought or sold.

99
00:07:01,450 --> 00:07:06,810
When there is a lot of liquidity, we say that
the orders can easily be absorbed by the markets.

100
00:07:06,810 --> 00:07:12,340
It means that there are many traders willing
to take the other side of your order.

101
00:07:12,340 --> 00:07:17,420
When there is little liquidity, it might be
harder to get your orders filled.

102
00:07:17,420 --> 00:07:21,710
Because there might not be enough traders
to take the other side of your trade at the

103
00:07:21,710 --> 00:07:27,340
price you want, you might get filled at a
worse price than expected.

104
00:07:27,340 --> 00:07:32,180
This is why some institutional traders use
special techniques to get a good price for

105
00:07:32,180 --> 00:07:33,550
their order.

106
00:07:33,550 --> 00:07:38,560
Whenever institutional traders need to open
a position, they do so with much larger size

107
00:07:38,560 --> 00:07:40,930
than the average retail trader.

108
00:07:40,930 --> 00:07:46,740
In fact, their positions are usually so big
that if they were to simply enter at once,

109
00:07:46,740 --> 00:07:48,300
they would move the market considerably.

110
00:07:48,300 --> 00:07:54,710
So when institutional traders need to enter
a large buy order, they will do so part by

111
00:07:54,710 --> 00:08:00,639
part, waiting for the price to come down before
pushing the next “slice” on the market.

112
00:08:00,639 --> 00:08:05,360
This creates patterns on the chart and the
more you trade supply and demand, the more

113
00:08:05,360 --> 00:08:10,550
you will “see” the underlying dynamics
of certain patterns that happen before supply

114
00:08:10,550 --> 00:08:13,540
and demand momentum drives.

115
00:08:13,540 --> 00:08:19,340
Another aspect is that institutional traders
understand where liquidity is accumulating.

116
00:08:19,340 --> 00:08:21,900
Let’s take this chart as an example.

117
00:08:21,900 --> 00:08:27,370
The institutional trader is looking for enough
liquidity to get a fill on his big order.

118
00:08:27,370 --> 00:08:32,789
He wants to go long, but he needs to find
traders who want to sell their position to

119
00:08:32,789 --> 00:08:33,789
him.

120
00:08:33,789 --> 00:08:38,559
Below the swing low, there will be lots of
that liquidity: first, you will have the stop

121
00:08:38,559 --> 00:08:43,870
losses of buy orders, which will sell on the
market once they’re hit.

122
00:08:43,870 --> 00:08:49,970
Additionally, there will also be traders who
go short, again adding liquidity to the market.

123
00:08:49,970 --> 00:08:54,579
This is why you will often first see a spike
in the opposite direction at the origin of

124
00:08:54,579 --> 00:08:56,350
a strong price move.

125
00:08:56,350 --> 00:09:02,050
The liquidity spike is the pattern that gets
created when large market participants need

126
00:09:02,050 --> 00:09:06,019
liquidity and move the market in order to
get it.

127
00:09:06,019 --> 00:09:11,139
Retail traders get trapped, their stops get
hit and they will often talk about “stop

128
00:09:11,139 --> 00:09:15,250
hunting” while in fact, this is nothing
more than normal market behavior.

129
00:09:15,250 --> 00:09:21,670
Monitor daily highs & lows, obvious swing
points and boundaries of ranges

130
00:09:21,670 --> 00:09:27,260
So now you know how smart money operates and
why they operate in a certain way.

131
00:09:27,260 --> 00:09:29,579
It’s time to find opportunities.

132
00:09:29,579 --> 00:09:34,470
The best way to do this, is to mark out certain
levels, such as:

133
00:09:34,470 --> 00:09:37,820
· Daily highs & lows
· Weekly highs & lows

134
00:09:37,820 --> 00:09:40,930
· Obvious swing points
· Boundaries of ranges

135
00:09:40,930 --> 00:09:48,059
By marking out these important areas of liquidity
and then analyzing what happens once the liquidity

136
00:09:48,059 --> 00:09:53,070
at these areas gets triggered, you can get
a better understanding of how smart money

137
00:09:53,070 --> 00:09:54,459
operates.

138
00:09:54,459 --> 00:09:59,649
You can then make up rules to develop an entire
strategy around this concept.

139
00:09:59,649 --> 00:10:05,589
Of course, the next step is to backtest the
rules and generate data to confirm a trading

140
00:10:05,589 --> 00:10:06,699
edge.

141
00:10:06,699 --> 00:10:11,890
One of the best ways to identify absorption
of liquidity by a bigger player, is to look

142
00:10:11,890 --> 00:10:15,850
at candle closes & the violence of moves.

143
00:10:15,850 --> 00:10:21,220
Is the high of a range being taken out, but
price quickly and aggressively falls back

144
00:10:21,220 --> 00:10:22,819
into the range?

145
00:10:22,819 --> 00:10:28,329
Then the buy side liquidity above the range
has been triggered and absorbed by smart money,

146
00:10:28,329 --> 00:10:30,759
to fill a short order.

147
00:10:30,759 --> 00:10:33,459
Waiting for confirmation is often very important.

148
00:10:33,459 --> 00:10:38,620
You want to see clear triggering of the liquidity
and then absorption of that liquidity, in

149
00:10:38,620 --> 00:10:46,759
order to join them.

150
00:10:46,759 --> 00:10:52,670
Smart money enter the markets to fill orders,
generate liquidity and to hedge their longer-term

151
00:10:52,670 --> 00:10:54,069
investments or trades

152
00:10:54,069 --> 00:10:55,069
Smart money enter the markets to fill orders,
generate liquidity and to hedge their longer-term

153
00:10:55,069 --> 00:10:56,069
investments or trades.

154
00:10:56,069 --> 00:10:57,879
This is not how us, retail traders, trade.

155
00:10:57,879 --> 00:11:01,860
This is the difference between retail trading
and institutional trading.

156
00:11:01,860 --> 00:11:05,240
We try to profit from small directional moves.

157
00:11:05,240 --> 00:11:07,779
So how to start trading like banks?

158
00:11:07,779 --> 00:11:12,740
Start with being as prepared as possible and
treat your trading like you are running a

159
00:11:12,740 --> 00:11:13,740
business.

160
00:11:13,740 --> 00:11:16,879
Banks don’t just let the RSI tell them when
to enter.

161
00:11:16,879 --> 00:11:20,259
Every position they take is well-calculated.

162
00:11:20,259 --> 00:11:25,009
They know exactly what they need to buy, when
they need to buy it and how they need to buy

163
00:11:25,009 --> 00:11:26,059
it.

164
00:11:26,059 --> 00:11:27,449
They know the costs involved.

165
00:11:27,449 --> 00:11:31,220
That’s how you should approach trading as
well.

166
00:11:31,220 --> 00:11:36,019
You can start trading like the smart money
by following the next principles:

167
00:11:36,019 --> 00:11:38,519
• Knowing your edge
• Having multiple plans

168
00:11:38,519 --> 00:11:44,009
• Reviewing & learning
These are the most important points to consider

169
00:11:44,009 --> 00:11:46,559
when you want to become a profitable trader.

170
00:11:46,559 --> 00:11:51,779
Not by learning a concept that banks “supposedly”
use, but by approaching trading the same as

171
00:11:51,779 --> 00:11:53,920
banks & professionals do.

172
00:11:53,920 --> 00:11:56,920
It’s absolutely vital to know your edge.

173
00:11:56,920 --> 00:11:59,500
Without an edge you will probably fail.

174
00:11:59,500 --> 00:12:00,570
How do you get one?

175
00:12:00,570 --> 00:12:03,600
By learning concepts that work in a market.

176
00:12:03,600 --> 00:12:07,279
Then you start with building rules around
these concepts.

177
00:12:07,279 --> 00:12:14,779
The next step is testing it on years of data,
followed by demo trading and live trading.

178
00:12:14,779 --> 00:12:20,269
In order to be able to execute your edge effectively
and in order to improve, you need multiple

179
00:12:20,269 --> 00:12:21,410
plans.

180
00:12:21,410 --> 00:12:26,759
You need a pre-market plan, a plan for executing
and a post market plan.

181
00:12:26,759 --> 00:12:31,649
A pre-market plan is all about how you find
the setups with your edge.

182
00:12:31,649 --> 00:12:35,009
How do you need to analyze the markets & when.

183
00:12:35,009 --> 00:12:36,899
Make this as clear as possible.

184
00:12:36,899 --> 00:12:39,949
This minimizes the mistakes you are going
to make.

185
00:12:39,949 --> 00:12:44,200
The most important thing is that you have
a clear, written down plan.

186
00:12:44,200 --> 00:12:46,940
After your session, it’s time to analyze.

187
00:12:46,940 --> 00:12:49,100
You will always make losing trades.

188
00:12:49,100 --> 00:12:54,089
Most traders simply go to the next trade,
if you also proceed this way, this means you

189
00:12:54,089 --> 00:12:55,809
wasted your money.

190
00:12:55,809 --> 00:13:00,619
But if you actually take the time to learn
from your losers, that’s not wasted money

191
00:13:00,619 --> 00:13:05,029
but simply a down payment for a valuable lesson.

192
00:13:05,029 --> 00:13:08,410
If you found value and learned something new,
leave us a like.

193
00:13:08,410 --> 00:13:11,940
This way we’ll know if you'd like to see
more videos like this one.

194
00:13:11,940 --> 00:13:17,350
And check out our academy program if you want
to further level up your trading.

195
00:13:17,350 --> 00:13:17,920
Until next time.

